00:00:21.990 --> 00:00:24.210
IAIN STEWART: So where were we?

00:00:24.210 --> 00:00:27.330
So last time, we were
talking about MS-bar scheme

00:00:27.330 --> 00:00:29.300
and renormalons.

00:00:29.300 --> 00:00:31.920
And so we talked about
the MS-bar scheme.

00:00:31.920 --> 00:00:33.180
We talked about renormalons.

00:00:33.180 --> 00:00:35.580
And we said that we could
introduce a mass scheme that

00:00:35.580 --> 00:00:39.790
has an arbitrary power log
cutoff, which we called R

00:00:39.790 --> 00:00:44.420
to distinguish it from mu, or
lambda or some other cutoff.

00:00:44.420 --> 00:00:48.620
And so the idea of
this scheme right

00:00:48.620 --> 00:00:53.558
here was perturbing
a way from MS-bar

00:00:53.558 --> 00:00:55.100
to get rid of this
renormalon problem

00:00:55.100 --> 00:00:59.430
that MS-bar has, but retain all
the nice features of MS-bar.

00:00:59.430 --> 00:01:02.450
In particular, we don't really
want to calculate anything new

00:01:02.450 --> 00:01:04.379
if we can avoid it.

00:01:04.379 --> 00:01:08.510
And that's what this scheme
does because really what it does

00:01:08.510 --> 00:01:11.600
is it uses the fact that we
know that the MS-bar scheme has

00:01:11.600 --> 00:01:13.280
this renormalon.

00:01:13.280 --> 00:01:15.740
So this series here
has a renormalon.

00:01:15.740 --> 00:01:18.530
And it just takes that
series over from MS-bar,

00:01:18.530 --> 00:01:21.350
puts it in with a
cutoff, which is this R,

00:01:21.350 --> 00:01:23.795
and defines a new mass
scheme using that formula.

00:01:27.460 --> 00:01:29.520
So this is like a
mass scheme that

00:01:29.520 --> 00:01:31.710
has an adjustable cutoff,
which we can take to be

00:01:31.710 --> 00:01:33.310
at whatever scale we want.

00:01:33.310 --> 00:01:34.830
And in particular,
at HQET, you'd

00:01:34.830 --> 00:01:38.280
want to take that R to be
something like a GeV type scale

00:01:38.280 --> 00:01:40.980
because that wouldn't
spoil your power counting.

00:01:40.980 --> 00:01:45.600
So recall, in HQET,
that this delta m

00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:48.900
should be, by power counting,
or order lambda QCD.

00:01:48.900 --> 00:01:54.730
So technically, you would take
R somewhat greater than lambda

00:01:54.730 --> 00:01:57.405
QCD, but of order lambda QCD.

00:02:00.070 --> 00:02:00.570
OK.

00:02:00.570 --> 00:02:02.310
So now, we have
this extra cutoff.

00:02:02.310 --> 00:02:05.350
So when we have a cutoff, we
have a renormalization group.

00:02:05.350 --> 00:02:07.200
And if you think about
the renormalization

00:02:07.200 --> 00:02:09.789
group for MS-bar mass, it
would be something like mu

00:02:09.789 --> 00:02:13.710
d by d mu of M of mu is equal
to anomalous dimension times M

00:02:13.710 --> 00:02:15.325
of mu back again.

00:02:15.325 --> 00:02:16.575
This one's a little different.

00:02:16.575 --> 00:02:19.140
It's R d by dR of
M of R. And then

00:02:19.140 --> 00:02:21.060
there's no M on the
right-hand side.

00:02:21.060 --> 00:02:25.250
It's an additive renormalization
to get rid of the renormalon.

00:02:25.250 --> 00:02:29.640
And there's a power,
also, of R here.

00:02:29.640 --> 00:02:32.910
So it's not just summing logs.

00:02:32.910 --> 00:02:35.310
It is summing some logs related
to the running of alpha,

00:02:35.310 --> 00:02:37.058
but it's also got this power.

00:02:37.058 --> 00:02:38.850
And when you solve this
anomalous dimension

00:02:38.850 --> 00:02:41.258
equation, which we
talked about last time,

00:02:41.258 --> 00:02:42.300
you get an integral like.

00:02:42.300 --> 00:02:45.060
In this t variable and
at leading log order,

00:02:45.060 --> 00:02:48.030
it looks like this, difference
of two incomplete gamma

00:02:48.030 --> 00:02:49.200
functions.

00:02:49.200 --> 00:02:51.000
Because of the
mass dimensions, it

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:52.530
has to be made up
by mass dimensions

00:02:52.530 --> 00:02:53.940
on the right-hand side.

00:02:53.940 --> 00:02:55.530
Coupling is dimensionless.

00:02:55.530 --> 00:02:58.230
The only thing that has
dimensions is lambda QCD.

00:02:58.230 --> 00:03:00.660
And that's exactly what pops
out of solving this equation.

00:03:00.660 --> 00:03:05.890
The R gets converted to a
lambda QCD by this formula here.

00:03:05.890 --> 00:03:09.270
This g of t was just
t at lowest order.

00:03:09.270 --> 00:03:11.140
So this is an
all-order form here.

00:03:11.140 --> 00:03:14.345
And this is the leading
log solution there.

00:03:14.345 --> 00:03:15.720
So if we look at
that leading log

00:03:15.720 --> 00:03:18.060
and what is the t0
or the t1, that's

00:03:18.060 --> 00:03:21.540
just the same formula
here, but with alpha

00:03:21.540 --> 00:03:25.560
at R1 and R0, the
boundary conditions.

00:03:25.560 --> 00:03:27.570
We want to run from R0 to R1.

00:03:27.570 --> 00:03:29.860
And this formula tells
us how to do that.

00:03:29.860 --> 00:03:32.760
And we get a result here
that has the coupling at R0

00:03:32.760 --> 00:03:35.820
and the coupling at R1.

00:03:35.820 --> 00:03:39.510
OK, so if we look at that
result, it's interesting.

00:03:39.510 --> 00:03:42.360
Because if we just had one
of these gamma functions,

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:44.280
these incomplete gamma
functions, then we

00:03:44.280 --> 00:03:45.950
would have a renormalon.

00:03:45.950 --> 00:03:50.050
And that's where I
stopped last time.

00:03:50.050 --> 00:03:54.760
So just looking at this
lambda QCD times gamma

00:03:54.760 --> 00:03:58.860
and expanding in a
series of about 0, which

00:03:58.860 --> 00:04:03.860
is expanding in the
coupling at infinity,

00:04:03.860 --> 00:04:06.540
you get this series, which
has a 2 to the n n factorial.

00:04:06.540 --> 00:04:07.860
It's an asymptotic series.

00:04:07.860 --> 00:04:10.020
This is a classic
example of a function

00:04:10.020 --> 00:04:13.570
that has an asymptotic series,
this incomplete gamma function.

00:04:13.570 --> 00:04:15.860
There's some exponential
that combines together

00:04:15.860 --> 00:04:19.829
with the lambda QCD to give an
R. So I pulled that out front.

00:04:19.829 --> 00:04:22.200
And then we have this
series, which is exactly u

00:04:22.200 --> 00:04:23.850
equals 1/2 renormalon.

00:04:23.850 --> 00:04:26.490
And the u equals 1/2 had to
do with this power 2 to the n

00:04:26.490 --> 00:04:29.190
here, the fact that
it's 2 to the n and not

00:04:29.190 --> 00:04:32.770
some other number.

00:04:32.770 --> 00:04:34.310
But if we take the
difference here--

00:04:34.310 --> 00:04:36.190
and this is what I said in
words last time, but now

00:04:36.190 --> 00:04:37.360
I'll write it down in equations.

00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:39.310
If we take the difference
there, that actually

00:04:39.310 --> 00:04:43.000
doesn't have this renormalon.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:52.710
So this is the difference
of two series, each of which

00:04:52.710 --> 00:04:53.710
is asymptotic.

00:05:02.932 --> 00:05:04.390
If we want to
compare those series,

00:05:04.390 --> 00:05:09.565
we should expand them in
the same coupling constant.

00:05:17.840 --> 00:05:18.720
So let me do that.

00:05:41.880 --> 00:05:45.290
So if I take the difference
of those two series using this

00:05:45.290 --> 00:05:49.260
formula, but now I re-expand all
these alphas in terms of alphas

00:05:49.260 --> 00:05:51.123
at the R1 scale--

00:05:51.123 --> 00:05:52.540
so when they're
at the R0 scale, I

00:05:52.540 --> 00:05:55.790
re-expand them in terms
of alpha at the R1 scale.

00:05:55.790 --> 00:05:57.050
Do some rearranging.

00:05:57.050 --> 00:06:00.440
I can write the result
in this form as this.

00:06:00.440 --> 00:06:03.330
So the key thing is
that difference there.

00:06:03.330 --> 00:06:05.810
And if you think about
what this sum here is,

00:06:05.810 --> 00:06:08.630
this is kind of like an
exponential, something

00:06:08.630 --> 00:06:10.250
to a power, k factorial.

00:06:10.250 --> 00:06:12.597
Except it's limited to n.

00:06:12.597 --> 00:06:14.930
So if I really went all the
way up to n equals infinity,

00:06:14.930 --> 00:06:16.880
this would be just giving
actually exponential

00:06:16.880 --> 00:06:18.275
of R1 over R0.

00:06:18.275 --> 00:06:23.150
It would cancel the R0 over R1,
which would then cancel the 1.

00:06:23.150 --> 00:06:26.420
You can rearrange the
series a little bit

00:06:26.420 --> 00:06:29.616
to make it more obvious
that it's convergent.

00:06:47.925 --> 00:06:49.550
Because there is this
n factorial here.

00:06:49.550 --> 00:06:51.650
And you might worry,
well, this thing here

00:06:51.650 --> 00:06:55.560
has to fall fast enough to
get rid of that n factorial.

00:06:55.560 --> 00:06:58.130
So write this thing out,
this 1, as an infinite series

00:06:58.130 --> 00:07:01.340
of terms from 0 to infinity
of the same form as this.

00:07:01.340 --> 00:07:05.390
And then what you're left
with is the following thing.

00:07:05.390 --> 00:07:08.000
All the terms from
0 to n cancel.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:10.250
And then you're just left
with the terms from n plus 1

00:07:10.250 --> 00:07:11.396
to infinity.

00:07:21.962 --> 00:07:23.670
And then you can see
that the n factorial

00:07:23.670 --> 00:07:26.040
is being tamed by another
factorial growth, which

00:07:26.040 --> 00:07:29.710
is always of a greater
power, n plus 1.

00:07:29.710 --> 00:07:32.670
OK, so this is a
number less than 1.

00:07:32.670 --> 00:07:36.900
And this thing here, beta 0
alpha over 2 pi times the log,

00:07:36.900 --> 00:07:39.368
is also something
that's less than 1.

00:07:39.368 --> 00:07:41.160
It's exactly the thing
that you sum up when

00:07:41.160 --> 00:07:42.928
you're running the coupling.

00:07:42.928 --> 00:07:44.220
So this is a convergent series.

00:07:55.300 --> 00:07:58.600
And basically the
physics of it is

00:07:58.600 --> 00:08:02.350
we had this mass that
didn't have a renormalon,

00:08:02.350 --> 00:08:04.257
but it had an arbitrary scale.

00:08:04.257 --> 00:08:06.340
And what the renormalization
group allows us to do

00:08:06.340 --> 00:08:08.243
is move to another scale.

00:08:08.243 --> 00:08:09.910
When we move to another
scale, it better

00:08:09.910 --> 00:08:12.340
be that we don't
reintroduce the renormalon.

00:08:12.340 --> 00:08:15.510
And the fact that I can write
this as a convergent series

00:08:15.510 --> 00:08:17.170
shows very explicitly
that I'm not

00:08:17.170 --> 00:08:20.140
having that problem in the
difference between these two.

00:08:28.870 --> 00:08:32.330
So it's renormalon free.

00:08:32.330 --> 00:08:36.870
And it remains renormalon
free when we change the scale.

00:08:36.870 --> 00:08:39.150
And we can sum up
these logarithms

00:08:39.150 --> 00:08:41.780
that have to do with
changing the scale.

00:08:50.610 --> 00:08:51.970
Why would you care about that?

00:08:51.970 --> 00:08:56.080
Well, imagine that you extract
this mass from some B physics.

00:08:56.080 --> 00:08:59.040
So you take an r.
that's of order GeV.

00:08:59.040 --> 00:09:01.410
And then you say, well,
that's a very precise number.

00:09:01.410 --> 00:09:04.835
But how do I use it for,
say, a LHC phenomenology?

00:09:04.835 --> 00:09:06.960
Well, if I want to connect
it to LHC phenomenology,

00:09:06.960 --> 00:09:10.020
I probably want to convert
to the MS-bar scheme

00:09:10.020 --> 00:09:11.430
because LHC is high energy.

00:09:11.430 --> 00:09:12.950
Maybe I'm doing Higgs to bb-bar.

00:09:12.950 --> 00:09:18.600
Bb-bar-- very energetic, so we
want to use the MS-bar scheme.

00:09:18.600 --> 00:09:20.903
But I've got this mass
at a very low scale.

00:09:20.903 --> 00:09:22.320
What you would
want to do is you'd

00:09:22.320 --> 00:09:24.240
want to use them the
renormalization group,

00:09:24.240 --> 00:09:29.260
run it up to the mass scale Mb,
switch schemes from this scheme

00:09:29.260 --> 00:09:31.740
where you extracted
the mass to MS-bar.

00:09:31.740 --> 00:09:34.170
You'd get a correspondingly
precise value of a MS-bar

00:09:34.170 --> 00:09:37.170
because the series between
this mass and the MS-bar mass

00:09:37.170 --> 00:09:39.920
is, again, a
renormalon free series.

00:09:39.920 --> 00:09:42.150
And then you could take
that mass at the Mb scale,

00:09:42.150 --> 00:09:44.160
run it up to, say,
the Higgs scale,

00:09:44.160 --> 00:09:46.122
and use it for phenomenology.

00:09:46.122 --> 00:09:47.580
So you always want
to be able to go

00:09:47.580 --> 00:09:49.165
back and forth between schemes.

00:09:49.165 --> 00:09:51.540
And if different schemes have
different scales associated

00:09:51.540 --> 00:09:55.020
to them, then you need to
the renormalization group

00:09:55.020 --> 00:09:58.200
in order to put them at
the same scale where you

00:09:58.200 --> 00:10:00.900
want to do the conversion, OK?

00:10:00.900 --> 00:10:03.900
So that's why being
able to sum up

00:10:03.900 --> 00:10:06.930
these logarithms without
reintroducing any renormalon

00:10:06.930 --> 00:10:09.758
problems is important.

00:10:13.180 --> 00:10:18.370
And in general, if you were
to try to do this with MS-bar,

00:10:18.370 --> 00:10:19.130
it wouldn't work.

00:10:23.780 --> 00:10:25.730
You don't really have
a way of treating

00:10:25.730 --> 00:10:27.800
the renormalon in the
MS-bar scheme when

00:10:27.800 --> 00:10:30.800
you're talking about physics
below the mass of the particle.

00:10:34.040 --> 00:10:37.500
OK, so we can generalize
this little discussion here,

00:10:37.500 --> 00:10:40.730
which was a fixed order
leading log discussion.

00:10:40.730 --> 00:10:43.430
And I can write down for
you just what would happen

00:10:43.430 --> 00:10:46.070
if I were to formally
integrate this integral here

00:10:46.070 --> 00:10:49.640
without making any
expansion in alpha S, OK?

00:11:00.830 --> 00:11:04.590
So express gamma R of t
as an infinite series.

00:11:04.590 --> 00:11:06.500
And it's an infant
series in alpha S.

00:11:06.500 --> 00:11:09.140
That means it's an infinite
series in 1 over t.

00:11:09.140 --> 00:11:13.550
We had an expression for this
capital G of t last time, which

00:11:13.550 --> 00:11:16.310
again was an infinite series.

00:11:16.310 --> 00:11:18.200
Just plug in those
infinite series.

00:11:18.200 --> 00:11:19.490
Do all the integrals.

00:11:19.490 --> 00:11:23.420
They all turned out to be
incomplete gamma functions, OK?

00:11:23.420 --> 00:11:29.280
So we can write
down a formula which

00:11:29.280 --> 00:11:31.350
is an all-order
generalization of that result

00:11:31.350 --> 00:11:34.737
just to see what happens
at higher orders.

00:11:34.737 --> 00:11:36.570
So basically, we would
have something like--

00:11:49.495 --> 00:11:52.260
if I look back at
what g of t was,

00:11:52.260 --> 00:11:54.450
we'd have something like this.

00:11:54.450 --> 00:11:56.760
And then all the
rest of the terms

00:11:56.760 --> 00:12:05.430
we can expand out in an inverse
Taylor series in 1 over t.

00:12:05.430 --> 00:12:07.193
So just there's
two terms in g of t

00:12:07.193 --> 00:12:08.610
I want to keep in
the exponential.

00:12:08.610 --> 00:12:10.860
And then the rest of them I
can expand out and combine

00:12:10.860 --> 00:12:11.568
with these terms.

00:12:11.568 --> 00:12:13.440
And that just gives
me some series.

00:12:13.440 --> 00:12:17.620
And I can do these integrals.

00:12:17.620 --> 00:12:37.390
So writing the integrand out,
we can just establish some

00:12:37.390 --> 00:12:47.858
notation for it for that
infinite series of 1 of t's.

00:12:47.858 --> 00:12:49.525
And we'll just call
the coefficients Sj.

00:12:55.290 --> 00:12:57.075
There is 1 over t.

00:13:02.170 --> 00:13:04.050
Yeah.

00:13:04.050 --> 00:13:07.198
So this gamma bar
starts as a 1 over t.

00:13:07.198 --> 00:13:12.438
So really it should be a
[INAUDIBLE] 1 over t here.

00:13:12.438 --> 00:13:13.980
That's where this
1 over t came from.

00:13:16.600 --> 00:13:20.730
So then integrate
that, and that gives us

00:13:20.730 --> 00:13:25.770
a generalization of this
formula here where we

00:13:25.770 --> 00:13:31.590
say that M of R1 minus
M of R0 where we work

00:13:31.590 --> 00:13:36.180
at some order in the
resummation, what you would say

00:13:36.180 --> 00:13:37.680
is, N to the KLL.

00:13:37.680 --> 00:13:39.930
So you have leading
log, next leading log,

00:13:39.930 --> 00:13:42.120
next to next leading log.

00:13:42.120 --> 00:13:44.970
And when you have K
of them, you say NKLL.

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:50.520
And the solution
of that equation

00:13:50.520 --> 00:14:00.600
would be the k-th order lambda
QCD and then this series.

00:14:07.590 --> 00:14:12.060
And instead of just the 0-th
incomplete gamma function,

00:14:12.060 --> 00:14:14.430
we get a slightly different one.

00:14:14.430 --> 00:14:16.290
But it's got the same
kind of structure

00:14:16.290 --> 00:14:18.420
where we get the difference
of gamma functions.

00:14:31.960 --> 00:14:33.550
And these S's are
just whatever you

00:14:33.550 --> 00:14:35.230
get from the
anomalous dimension,

00:14:35.230 --> 00:14:37.985
so kind of simple notation.

00:14:50.132 --> 00:14:51.630
[INAUDIBLE]

00:14:51.630 --> 00:14:54.220
So they're just some
combination of numbers.

00:14:54.220 --> 00:14:56.110
And the twiddles here
is just my shorthand

00:14:56.110 --> 00:15:00.790
for accounting for
a fact that there's

00:15:00.790 --> 00:15:04.500
some beta 0s floating around.

00:15:04.500 --> 00:15:05.500
So this is just algebra.

00:15:09.540 --> 00:15:11.650
And these b1 hats
and b2 hats were

00:15:11.650 --> 00:15:15.790
things that showed up in
the beta function of QCD,

00:15:15.790 --> 00:15:19.250
which we also talked
about last time.

00:15:19.250 --> 00:15:20.920
So we defined those last time.

00:15:20.920 --> 00:15:24.370
The b1 hat and b2 hat were
just combinations of the beta 1

00:15:24.370 --> 00:15:29.120
and beta 2 and beta 0.

00:15:29.120 --> 00:15:31.600
So these are some numbers
that you can calculate

00:15:31.600 --> 00:15:33.338
given the anomalous dimensions.

00:15:33.338 --> 00:15:35.630
Given those numbers, you can
plug it into this formula.

00:15:35.630 --> 00:15:38.860
And then you have
a generalization

00:15:38.860 --> 00:15:40.070
of the previous result.

00:15:40.070 --> 00:15:42.445
So whatever order you know
the anomalous dimension to you

00:15:42.445 --> 00:15:43.750
can use that solution.

00:15:43.750 --> 00:15:46.375
And we'll use it a little later
when I talk about some numbers.

00:15:51.180 --> 00:15:53.750
All right, so any
questions so far?

