There's a similar
thing for MS-bar mass.

00:16:01.380 --> 00:16:03.395
If you were summing
logs of the MS-bar mass,

00:16:03.395 --> 00:16:04.770
there's an all-orders
formula you

00:16:04.770 --> 00:16:07.263
could write down
and use once you

00:16:07.263 --> 00:16:09.130
know the anomalous dimensions.

00:16:09.130 --> 00:16:13.340
You could find it in the
particle data book I think.

00:16:13.340 --> 00:16:18.810
All right, so just coming back
to this comment about the fact

00:16:18.810 --> 00:16:21.450
that the anomalous dimension
is renormalon free--

00:16:26.430 --> 00:16:29.205
so the fact that the solution
here was renormalon free,

00:16:29.205 --> 00:16:31.080
that the difference here
was renormalon free,

00:16:31.080 --> 00:16:32.600
was because there
was no renormalon

00:16:32.600 --> 00:16:35.100
on the right-hand side here and
that the anomalous dimension

00:16:35.100 --> 00:16:37.668
was renormalon free.

00:16:37.668 --> 00:16:39.210
And it was constructed
from something

00:16:39.210 --> 00:16:44.940
that had a renormalon,
which is this delta M,

00:16:44.940 --> 00:16:48.330
but it was a derivative
of that delta M.

00:16:48.330 --> 00:16:53.440
And so the derivative
kills the renormalon.

00:16:53.440 --> 00:17:00.430
So this thing is free of the
delta M of order lambda QCD

00:17:00.430 --> 00:17:04.655
renormalon because that
renormalon is a constant.

00:17:04.655 --> 00:17:06.030
And when you take
the derivative,

00:17:06.030 --> 00:17:07.170
you kill the constant.

00:17:07.170 --> 00:17:09.869
That's how you can think of it.

00:17:09.869 --> 00:17:13.500
If you start writing
out the gamma functions,

00:17:13.500 --> 00:17:16.714
then you see that it looks like
you're finding the renormalon.

00:17:16.714 --> 00:17:18.089
But then there's
some differences

00:17:18.089 --> 00:17:21.030
that show up and cancel it off.

00:17:21.030 --> 00:17:24.810
So the way that that
works, it's kind

00:17:24.810 --> 00:17:26.310
of like this where
you sort of think

00:17:26.310 --> 00:17:27.630
that you have the
renormalon, but then you

00:17:27.630 --> 00:17:29.760
realize there's another
term and it cancels it off.

00:17:48.830 --> 00:17:55.760
So if we look back at
our formula for delta M,

00:17:55.760 --> 00:17:58.660
this had an infinite
series of a's.

00:17:58.660 --> 00:18:01.310
This was like a sum over
sum a n's, and some alpha

00:18:01.310 --> 00:18:05.300
to the n, some other factors.

00:18:05.300 --> 00:18:07.370
And these gammas are
just related to the a's.

00:18:12.260 --> 00:18:13.940
But they're not just
related to the a's.

00:18:13.940 --> 00:18:17.330
They're also factors of the
beta function that come in.

00:18:17.330 --> 00:18:20.390
So just to give you an idea--

00:18:25.625 --> 00:18:28.890
so once you know the scheme
conversion to the scheme

00:18:28.890 --> 00:18:33.670
and you know the
anomalous dimension

00:18:33.670 --> 00:18:35.930
and if you look at this
series and you think about

00:18:35.930 --> 00:18:37.910
whether the series for
the anomalous dimension

00:18:37.910 --> 00:18:48.570
is convergent or
asymptotic, you can sort of

00:18:48.570 --> 00:18:51.702
identify the pattern of how
these coefficients look.

00:18:51.702 --> 00:18:53.160
And basically, if
you, for example,

00:18:53.160 --> 00:18:56.460
look at the bubble
sum, this a n plus 1

00:18:56.460 --> 00:18:59.250
would be something
that has an n factorial

00:18:59.250 --> 00:19:03.720
2 beta 0 to the n plus 1--

00:19:03.720 --> 00:19:07.060
sorry, to the n growth.

00:19:07.060 --> 00:19:14.640
And then this thing here is
n minus 1 factorial to beta 0

00:19:14.640 --> 00:19:17.040
to the n minus 1.

00:19:17.040 --> 00:19:21.690
And then there's this extra
2n beta 0 that multiplies it.

00:19:21.690 --> 00:19:24.390
And you can see that there
is an exact cancellation.

00:19:27.220 --> 00:19:29.220
One way of probing
the renormalon

00:19:29.220 --> 00:19:30.780
is just to look
at the bubble sum.

00:19:30.780 --> 00:19:33.900
And the bubble sum gave us a
particular value of these a's.

00:19:33.900 --> 00:19:37.115
And you can see that the bubble
sum renormalon is cancelling

00:19:37.115 --> 00:19:38.240
out between the terms here.

00:19:47.170 --> 00:19:50.550
So that's just an expression
of what I said over here.

00:19:50.550 --> 00:19:53.400
That's the kind of more
definite expression of the fact

00:19:53.400 --> 00:19:55.657
that this thing is actually
free of the renormalon.

00:19:59.717 --> 00:20:01.550
So I'm going to put
this aside for a minute.

00:20:01.550 --> 00:20:03.470
And we'll come back in to
use this formula a little bit

00:20:03.470 --> 00:20:04.580
later in today's lecture.

00:20:08.698 --> 00:20:11.240
So there's sort of two ways that
you can use this technology.

00:20:11.240 --> 00:20:14.660
You can use it as a means
of doing what I said,

00:20:14.660 --> 00:20:16.450
of connecting masses
at different scales

00:20:16.450 --> 00:20:17.450
and doing phenomenology.

00:20:17.450 --> 00:20:20.160
And we'll come back to
that a little bit later.

00:20:20.160 --> 00:20:23.163
But you could also use it as
a probe of the renormalon.

00:20:23.163 --> 00:20:25.580
So one thing that you might
complain about with the bubble

00:20:25.580 --> 00:20:28.757
sum is that it's just some
arbitrarily chosen way

00:20:28.757 --> 00:20:29.840
of probing the renormalon.

00:20:29.840 --> 00:20:32.150
And maybe there's some
problem where you don't

00:20:32.150 --> 00:20:33.620
have light fermions around.

00:20:33.620 --> 00:20:35.500
Maybe you only have gluons.

00:20:35.500 --> 00:20:38.160
And there could still be a
renormalon in those problems.

00:20:38.160 --> 00:20:40.730
So how would you
deal with that if you

00:20:40.730 --> 00:20:43.280
didn't have the light
quarks available to make up

00:20:43.280 --> 00:20:44.000
this bubble sum?

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:45.950
Or maybe there's
some renormalon that

00:20:45.950 --> 00:20:49.010
just so happens you don't
see it with the quarks.

00:20:49.010 --> 00:20:50.270
There's no guarantee of that.

00:20:50.270 --> 00:20:52.220
So you'd like to have
some other mechanism

00:20:52.220 --> 00:20:53.900
for looking for renormalons.

00:20:53.900 --> 00:20:56.570
And you can actually use
the renormalization group

00:20:56.570 --> 00:20:58.657
to do that, which is
kind of interesting.

00:20:58.657 --> 00:20:59.990
So I'll show you how that works.

00:21:10.935 --> 00:21:12.560
A nice thing about
this is that it also

00:21:12.560 --> 00:21:15.310
makes it clear how
the renormalon relates

00:21:15.310 --> 00:21:16.427
to the Landau pole.

00:21:16.427 --> 00:21:17.510
So we'll see that as well.

00:21:25.420 --> 00:21:28.912
So take our solution
for the RGE,

00:21:28.912 --> 00:21:30.870
which we could write in
terms of this integral.

00:21:41.768 --> 00:21:43.810
And let's consider what
this integral actually is

00:21:43.810 --> 00:21:47.060
doing in the complex t plane.

00:21:47.060 --> 00:21:58.210
So the t's are negative,
and so they look like this.

00:21:58.210 --> 00:22:01.540
The Landau pole where
the coupling blows up

00:22:01.540 --> 00:22:03.920
is where the t goes to 0.

00:22:03.920 --> 00:22:05.645
So the Landau pole
is at the origin.

00:22:08.822 --> 00:22:10.780
So this is what the
complex t plane looks like.

00:22:13.482 --> 00:22:15.440
And what we're doing when
we do the integral is

00:22:15.440 --> 00:22:19.040
we're just doing an integral
over that little range

00:22:19.040 --> 00:22:20.690
here, right?

00:22:20.690 --> 00:22:22.460
So we're far away
from the Landau pole.

00:22:22.460 --> 00:22:24.418
And that's why everything
was nicely convergent

00:22:24.418 --> 00:22:28.210
and you could connect
one mass to another.

00:22:28.210 --> 00:22:31.220
But you could ask, what
happens if I take this t0

00:22:31.220 --> 00:22:34.240
and I move it somewhere
else in this picture?

00:22:34.240 --> 00:22:36.720
And that's what
we're going to do.

00:22:36.720 --> 00:22:39.980
So let's consider the
limit where R0 goes to 0.

00:22:44.090 --> 00:22:47.240
If R goes to 0 and you
look back at the formula

00:22:47.240 --> 00:22:50.150
that we had that converts
between the MS-bar mass

00:22:50.150 --> 00:22:56.375
and this M of R, you'll see
that M of R0 goes to M pole.

00:22:59.750 --> 00:23:02.420
Because we had a power of
R times a series of alpha

00:23:02.420 --> 00:23:04.010
of R's, which are
just logs of R.

00:23:04.010 --> 00:23:06.380
The power always
wins, and so the mass

00:23:06.380 --> 00:23:11.990
goes to the pole mass and
that limit that R0 goes to 0.

00:23:11.990 --> 00:23:20.420
And if you look
at what T0 is, T0

00:23:20.420 --> 00:23:22.730
is related to the
coupling, which

00:23:22.730 --> 00:23:25.850
I could write in terms
of a log of lambda QCD.

00:23:25.850 --> 00:23:30.390
And T0 is basically in this
limit going to plus infinity.

00:23:30.390 --> 00:23:33.200
So what happens is, if I want
to get back to the pole mass

00:23:33.200 --> 00:23:37.010
from one of these masses, I
basically have to take this guy

00:23:37.010 --> 00:23:39.830
and move out to
infinity, which means

00:23:39.830 --> 00:23:42.800
I have to make a choice about
going around that Landau pole.

00:24:01.900 --> 00:24:04.036
So basically, you're
taking your RGE

00:24:04.036 --> 00:24:06.530
and you're pushing
it into a region

00:24:06.530 --> 00:24:12.680
where you're no longer
completely perturbative

00:24:12.680 --> 00:24:16.640
and that you're forced to
continue by Landau pole.

00:24:21.140 --> 00:24:23.698
Now, you can actually
avoid the Landau pole.

00:24:28.550 --> 00:24:30.770
It's true that
the series becomes

00:24:30.770 --> 00:24:33.230
non-perturbative in this
region, but you could go way up

00:24:33.230 --> 00:24:36.350
here and come back over there.

00:24:36.350 --> 00:24:39.800
So you can actually
formally stay

00:24:39.800 --> 00:24:41.720
in a region in the
complex plane where

00:24:41.720 --> 00:24:45.615
you're perturbation theory
is still applicable.

00:24:45.615 --> 00:24:47.490
But you still have to
decide which way you're

00:24:47.490 --> 00:24:50.320
going to go around it.

00:24:50.320 --> 00:24:52.490
And so that introduces
an ambiguity.

00:25:04.370 --> 00:25:19.627
So doing that, say we
go above or something.

00:25:27.420 --> 00:25:34.520
And if you plug in this result,
the lowest order leading log

00:25:34.520 --> 00:25:48.600
result, you get this integral.

00:25:48.600 --> 00:25:50.580
And this integral,
you know, you have

00:25:50.580 --> 00:25:55.603
to go around the t equals 0
pole because t1 is negative.

00:25:55.603 --> 00:25:58.020
So it turns out that you can
actually take this integral--

00:25:58.020 --> 00:26:00.180
and I'm going to leave
this for your problem set--

00:26:08.690 --> 00:26:21.115
and write it in the
form of a Borel integral

00:26:21.115 --> 00:26:25.360
with an exponential that's
exactly the Borel transform

00:26:25.360 --> 00:26:26.750
variable.

00:26:26.750 --> 00:26:30.410
So I just change the
variable from t to u.

00:26:30.410 --> 00:26:32.840
So I get this integral.

00:26:32.840 --> 00:26:38.330
And if you do that, what
you find is that f of u

00:26:38.330 --> 00:26:43.800
is proportional to
1 over u minus 1/2.

00:26:43.800 --> 00:26:45.800
AUDIENCE: What's the lower
limit of integration?

00:26:45.800 --> 00:26:47.136
IAIN STEWART: 0.

00:26:47.136 --> 00:26:47.636
Yeah.

00:26:51.080 --> 00:26:55.590
OK, so you can actually see that
the RGE and what was the Landau

00:26:55.590 --> 00:26:58.710
pole here is effectively,
in this integral here,

00:26:58.710 --> 00:27:01.050
becoming this Borel
pole at u equals 1/2.

00:27:11.700 --> 00:27:14.970
And that makes a little
more clear the fact

00:27:14.970 --> 00:27:18.570
that these poles are related
to the non-perturbative physics

00:27:18.570 --> 00:27:22.260
that's in the coupling
and the infrared physics.

00:27:24.820 --> 00:27:26.220
So formally, this
actually allows

00:27:26.220 --> 00:27:31.950
you to set up a method of
trying to find the renormalon.

00:27:31.950 --> 00:27:36.900
You can ask, given some
series, if I sort of construct

00:27:36.900 --> 00:27:40.393
this thing, what if I
just had this attitude

00:27:40.393 --> 00:27:42.810
that we want to pick that
series to cancel the renormalon?

00:27:42.810 --> 00:27:44.227
Now, take the
attitude, what if we

00:27:44.227 --> 00:27:47.150
didn't know that that
series had a renormalon?

00:27:47.150 --> 00:27:49.860
I could still throw it in,
make a change of variable

00:27:49.860 --> 00:27:51.420
to some mass.

00:27:51.420 --> 00:27:53.160
If it's a convergent
series, then I'm

00:27:53.160 --> 00:27:55.285
just defining some new mass.

00:27:55.285 --> 00:27:56.910
And I could go through
this technology.

00:27:56.910 --> 00:28:03.430
And it should turn out that, if
the series was OK, so to speak,

00:28:03.430 --> 00:28:06.510
then you wouldn't
find this renormalon.

00:28:06.510 --> 00:28:07.920
You wouldn't find a pole there.

00:28:11.100 --> 00:28:12.540
I won't go through
this in detail

00:28:12.540 --> 00:28:17.520
because it is a bit
tricky to derive.

00:28:17.520 --> 00:28:21.570
But you can derive what's called
a sum rule for the renormalon,

00:28:21.570 --> 00:28:25.560
which is another way of
probing it by basically

00:28:25.560 --> 00:28:28.270
taking our all-order solution.

00:28:28.270 --> 00:28:32.400
So I took our leading
log solution here, right?

00:28:32.400 --> 00:28:35.850
If I did the same thing
with the all-order solution,

00:28:35.850 --> 00:28:39.360
I could also take the
Borel transform of that.

00:28:39.360 --> 00:28:42.675
And that, if I do that, gives me
this thing called the sum rule.

00:29:01.570 --> 00:29:03.870
So it's just manipulating
an infinite series.

00:29:03.870 --> 00:29:08.530
And Mathematica can sum
some of them up for you.

00:29:08.530 --> 00:29:14.430
So it's just tedious.

00:29:20.070 --> 00:29:29.890
And what you find is a formula
for the residue of the Borel

00:29:29.890 --> 00:29:31.610
pole.

00:29:31.610 --> 00:29:33.850
So let me call
that residue P 1/2.

00:29:43.220 --> 00:29:45.110
And the answer is
actually pretty simple.

00:29:57.780 --> 00:29:59.450
So these S's were
these coefficients

00:29:59.450 --> 00:30:01.040
that were showing
up in our solution

00:30:01.040 --> 00:30:03.620
for the all-orders RGE.

00:30:03.620 --> 00:30:06.410
P 1/2 is a series
which will tell me

00:30:06.410 --> 00:30:08.810
the residue of the pole.

00:30:08.810 --> 00:30:13.980
So that means that, if
P 1/2 is not equal to 0,

00:30:13.980 --> 00:30:15.650
then you have a u
equals 1/2 pole.

00:30:24.520 --> 00:30:32.900
And if 1/2 is equal to 0, then
you have no u equals 1/2 pole.

00:30:32.900 --> 00:30:36.140
Now, in practice, you don't
have an all-orders result.

00:30:36.140 --> 00:30:38.497
You only know a finite
number of these S's.

00:30:38.497 --> 00:30:40.580
So what you actually do
is you look at this series

00:30:40.580 --> 00:30:44.000
and try to figure out where
it's converging to, OK?

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:46.160
But actually, even
with the knowledge

00:30:46.160 --> 00:30:50.120
that we have of the series, for
example, for the b quark mass,

00:30:50.120 --> 00:30:53.390
you can very quickly see that
it has a u equals 1/2 pole.

00:30:53.390 --> 00:30:55.072
And you can even do
some error analysis

00:30:55.072 --> 00:30:56.030
by varying some things.

00:30:56.030 --> 00:30:59.810
And you get some kind of ID
of the theoretical uncertainty

00:30:59.810 --> 00:31:02.000
from higher order
terms in the series.

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:06.232
If you just formally, say, take
a series that's convergent,

00:31:06.232 --> 00:31:07.940
if I hand you a series
that's convergent,

00:31:07.940 --> 00:31:10.760
you can calculate
all these SK's.

00:31:10.760 --> 00:31:14.410
And then you can very easily
see that actually there's no u

00:31:14.410 --> 00:31:15.080
equals 1/2 pole.

00:31:15.080 --> 00:31:17.740
What happens is that all the
terms are cancelling in this

00:31:17.740 --> 00:31:20.953
series, and you just get 0.

00:31:20.953 --> 00:31:23.120
So it's kind of like the
cancellations I was talking

00:31:23.120 --> 00:31:26.480
about where I was cancelling
a poll in the anomalous

00:31:26.480 --> 00:31:29.000
dimension, but here it's
happening in this thing if I

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:30.080
have a convergent series.

00:31:30.080 --> 00:31:33.050
So this is a way of probing
for renormalons, which

00:31:33.050 --> 00:31:34.790
doesn't rely on the bubble sum.

00:31:34.790 --> 00:31:37.160
And it basically uses the
perturbative information

00:31:37.160 --> 00:31:41.900
that you have available, whether
it's non-abelian or abelian

00:31:41.900 --> 00:31:42.560
information.

00:31:42.560 --> 00:31:43.380
AUDIENCE: Iain?

00:31:43.380 --> 00:31:45.100
IAIN STEWART: Yeah?

00:31:45.100 --> 00:31:47.930
AUDIENCE: So when you did,
well, this calculation

00:31:47.930 --> 00:31:51.740
here, that capital F, is it the
same result as we found a week

00:31:51.740 --> 00:31:54.840
and a half ago or something
that has the renormalon at u

00:31:54.840 --> 00:31:56.545
equals 1 and all
that stuff as well?

00:31:56.545 --> 00:31:58.788
IAIN STEWART: No, it's
just the u equals 1/2 pole.

00:31:58.788 --> 00:31:59.830
AUDIENCE: So [INAUDIBLE].

00:31:59.830 --> 00:32:00.390
IAIN STEWART: Yeah.

00:32:00.390 --> 00:32:00.560
Yeah.

00:32:00.560 --> 00:32:02.340
AUDIENCE: So what happened
to the [INAUDIBLE]??

00:32:02.340 --> 00:32:03.173
IAIN STEWART: Right.

00:32:03.173 --> 00:32:05.540
So what we've done here--

00:32:05.540 --> 00:32:07.607
and actually, I'm just
going to come to this,

00:32:07.607 --> 00:32:08.440
but I'll foreshadow.

00:32:08.440 --> 00:32:10.690
So what we've done
here is we set up

00:32:10.690 --> 00:32:13.870
a construction to remove
the u equals 1/2 pole.

00:32:13.870 --> 00:32:17.320
And we did not remove
any higher poles.

00:32:17.320 --> 00:32:19.460
We said the u equals 1/2
is the most important.

00:32:19.460 --> 00:32:22.390
Let's get rid of that
one from the MS-bar mass.

00:32:22.390 --> 00:32:24.710
There would be, in
principle, higher ones.

00:32:24.710 --> 00:32:27.500
And higher ones,
basically, we had

00:32:27.500 --> 00:32:33.340
something that was proportional
to R. That's for u equals 1/2.

00:32:33.340 --> 00:32:34.840
If you wanted to
remove higher ones,

00:32:34.840 --> 00:32:37.660
you'd need terms proportional
to R squared, for example, for u

00:32:37.660 --> 00:32:40.580
equals 1, et cetera.

00:32:40.580 --> 00:32:43.707
So we could have added
more terms to do more,

00:32:43.707 --> 00:32:44.290
but we didn't.

00:32:44.290 --> 00:32:46.930
We just sort of removed the
problem at u equals 1/2.

00:32:46.930 --> 00:32:48.910
And that's why, when
we go through this,

00:32:48.910 --> 00:32:51.376
you only see a u
equals 1/2 pole.

00:32:51.376 --> 00:32:54.328
AUDIENCE: So if you wanted
to do [INAUDIBLE] analysis

00:32:54.328 --> 00:32:56.620
or something, you'd have to
change the result of this--

00:32:56.620 --> 00:32:56.870
IAIN STEWART: Yeah.

00:32:56.870 --> 00:32:58.375
So the way you
should think about it

00:32:58.375 --> 00:33:00.250
is that basically what
you're doing is you're

00:33:00.250 --> 00:33:04.300
setting up a scheme change that
perturbatively takes you out

00:33:04.300 --> 00:33:06.580
of MS-bar towards
something else.

00:33:06.580 --> 00:33:10.260
You remove the u equals 1/2,
and you get rid of that problem.

00:33:10.260 --> 00:33:12.760
If you thought you had enough
perturbative accuracy that you

00:33:12.760 --> 00:33:14.620
were seeing problems
related to u equals 1,

00:33:14.620 --> 00:33:16.730
then you could make
further scheme change

00:33:16.730 --> 00:33:19.490
with another series that's
proportional to R squared

00:33:19.490 --> 00:33:21.982
to get rid of that one.

00:33:21.982 --> 00:33:23.860
AUDIENCE: Wait,
so the Landau pole

00:33:23.860 --> 00:33:25.570
would tell you about
all the renormalons?

00:33:25.570 --> 00:33:27.280
IAIN STEWART: It would tell you
about these ones, too. yeah,

00:33:27.280 --> 00:33:28.430
absolutely.

00:33:28.430 --> 00:33:33.610
So you can actually generalize
this for R to the P.

00:33:33.610 --> 00:33:35.680
And you can derive a
sum rule for R to the P.

00:33:35.680 --> 00:33:37.990
And it's a slightly more
complicated formula here.

00:33:37.990 --> 00:33:40.825
And then you'd have
the P over 2 pole.

00:33:45.170 --> 00:33:57.810
All right, OK, so the sum rule
is a probe, alternate probe,

00:33:57.810 --> 00:33:59.468
for the renormalon.

00:34:08.432 --> 00:34:13.219
The nf bubbles are the classic
one that people know about.

00:34:13.219 --> 00:34:16.159
And this provides an alternate.

00:34:16.159 --> 00:34:17.659
The nice thing about
this is it also

00:34:17.659 --> 00:34:20.480
provides a series that you can
look at the convergence, where

00:34:20.480 --> 00:34:23.600
the nf bubbles just get a
result. See, nf bubbles are

00:34:23.600 --> 00:34:26.449
good for finding
out whether or not

00:34:26.449 --> 00:34:28.250
this thing has a renormalon.

00:34:28.250 --> 00:34:31.909
If you get some non-0 result,
then you expect that it does.

00:34:31.909 --> 00:34:35.300
This way you could actually
calculate the residue

00:34:35.300 --> 00:34:38.900
if you wanted to know that
value for some reason.

00:34:38.900 --> 00:34:39.400
OK.

00:34:43.837 --> 00:34:46.123
Now, that actually might
be useful, for example,

00:34:46.123 --> 00:34:48.290
if you wanted to think about
higher renormalon poles

00:34:48.290 --> 00:34:50.060
because you might
want to say, well,

00:34:50.060 --> 00:34:52.690
let me get rid of the first
one with whatever residue

00:34:52.690 --> 00:34:54.800
I can best approximate
for and see if there's

00:34:54.800 --> 00:34:56.827
another one underneath.

00:34:56.827 --> 00:34:58.910
There's not really enough
perturbative information

00:34:58.910 --> 00:35:01.590
that we have about QCD to be
able to do that type of thing.

00:35:01.590 --> 00:35:04.185
There's a few cases where
u equals 1/2 is absent,

00:35:04.185 --> 00:35:05.810
and then you can do
that kind of thing.

00:35:05.810 --> 00:35:07.010
I mean, there's
actually many cases

00:35:07.010 --> 00:35:08.300
where u equals 1/2
is absent, and you

00:35:08.300 --> 00:35:09.230
can look for u equals 1.

00:35:09.230 --> 00:35:10.897
But looking for a
sub-leading renormalon

00:35:10.897 --> 00:35:15.080
is something that
nobody's found one.

00:35:15.080 --> 00:35:19.370
People sometimes
speculate about them

00:35:19.370 --> 00:35:23.997
because maybe the residue of the
first one happens to be small.

00:35:23.997 --> 00:35:25.580
This would allow you
to test for that.

00:35:30.340 --> 00:35:32.320
In the tau decays
people talk about that.

00:35:35.530 --> 00:35:39.700
OK, so let's come back
and actually show you

00:35:39.700 --> 00:35:42.340
how you can use this technology
for some phenomenological

00:35:42.340 --> 00:35:43.570
stuff.

00:35:43.570 --> 00:35:46.180
And I want to do that by
generalizing our discussion

00:35:46.180 --> 00:35:50.590
slightly away from masses
towards just a general operator

00:35:50.590 --> 00:35:53.180
product expansion.

00:35:53.180 --> 00:35:55.240
So everything that we've
said here for masses

00:35:55.240 --> 00:36:02.020
can be applied more generally to
an operator product expansion.

00:36:02.020 --> 00:36:05.153
So let me show you what I mean.

00:36:05.153 --> 00:36:07.570
So let's first consider what
I mean by an operator product

00:36:07.570 --> 00:36:09.980
expansion at MS-bar.

00:36:09.980 --> 00:36:12.847
So you can think of this like
maybe I'm integrating out

00:36:12.847 --> 00:36:13.555
a heavy particle.

00:36:16.860 --> 00:36:19.690
And I'm writing a
formula down, and it

00:36:19.690 --> 00:36:21.100
has some Wilson coefficients.

00:36:21.100 --> 00:36:24.040
It has some operators.

00:36:24.040 --> 00:36:26.590
And it's a Taylor
series in this parameter

00:36:26.590 --> 00:36:31.035
q, which is the hard
scale, high energy scale.

00:36:31.035 --> 00:36:32.410
And I'm basically
just expanding,

00:36:32.410 --> 00:36:37.700
if you like, in lambda QCD
over Q. And the operators,

00:36:37.700 --> 00:36:40.750
they're set by lambda QCD.

00:36:40.750 --> 00:36:43.960
So I'm going to take this
guy to be dimensionless.

00:36:43.960 --> 00:36:47.970
This is some
dimensionless observable.

00:36:47.970 --> 00:36:49.560
You can always make
it dimensionless

00:36:49.560 --> 00:36:54.330
by a suitably choosing,
multiplying by appropriate math

00:36:54.330 --> 00:36:55.810
scales.

00:36:55.810 --> 00:36:58.150
So then this here will
be a dimensionless Wilson

00:36:58.150 --> 00:37:00.180
coefficient.

00:37:00.180 --> 00:37:03.460
And it's a Wilson
coefficient in MS-bar.

00:37:03.460 --> 00:37:05.900
That's what the bar means.

00:37:05.900 --> 00:37:09.230
And so this is an MS-bar
operator, MS-bar matrix element

00:37:09.230 --> 00:37:10.464
of some operator.

00:37:13.070 --> 00:37:14.562
And it's also dimensionless.

00:37:17.730 --> 00:37:21.365
So this guy will be
dimensionless, too.

00:37:21.365 --> 00:37:23.490
And finally, this guy will
have dimension equals 1.

00:37:28.730 --> 00:37:30.830
Now, at MS-bar, what's
beautiful about MS-bar

00:37:30.830 --> 00:37:35.150
is that the series for these
coefficients are very simple.

00:37:35.150 --> 00:37:37.940
That's why people like
to compute in MS-bar.

00:37:49.570 --> 00:37:56.030
So if you look at what the
series for C bar looks like,

00:37:56.030 --> 00:37:58.670
the form of it is as follows.

00:38:04.400 --> 00:38:09.170
It's got dependence on mu
over Q and alpha s of mu.

00:38:13.850 --> 00:38:17.330
And these guys here are
not an arbitrary function

00:38:17.330 --> 00:38:20.450
of mu over Q, but they're
really just some logs.

00:38:20.450 --> 00:38:22.430
So this looks like
a series of logs.

00:38:25.520 --> 00:38:29.830
So in MS-bar, you're only
seeing these logarithms.

00:38:29.830 --> 00:38:43.400
So that's good from a
computational point of view,

00:38:43.400 --> 00:38:45.080
but we also know
that generically,

00:38:45.080 --> 00:38:48.500
in this MS-bar approach,
you might get sensitivity

00:38:48.500 --> 00:38:50.090
to renormalons.

00:38:56.330 --> 00:38:58.370
Also, another thing
we like about MS-bar

00:38:58.370 --> 00:39:01.370
is that it satisfies all the
symmetries we want to keep.

00:39:01.370 --> 00:39:02.480
It doesn't mess them up.

00:39:02.480 --> 00:39:05.292
So it's Lorentz and
gauge invariant,

00:39:05.292 --> 00:39:06.500
which is always a good thing.

00:39:13.280 --> 00:39:16.190
And not only is it simple
for multi-loop computations,

00:39:16.190 --> 00:39:19.310
but multi-loop computations are
not even done in other schemes

00:39:19.310 --> 00:39:21.118
because they're
just too difficult.

00:39:21.118 --> 00:39:23.285
So it really makes multi-loop
computations possible.

00:39:28.970 --> 00:39:31.460
And the but, there's
only really this one but,

00:39:31.460 --> 00:39:36.060
that it has this
renormalon issue.

00:39:41.120 --> 00:39:43.400
So we talked about
renormalon for a mass.

00:39:43.400 --> 00:39:46.910
And I just showed you what it
was, and then we explored it.

00:39:46.910 --> 00:39:50.960
Here, let me tell you what
the renormalon would be.

00:39:50.960 --> 00:39:54.170
So generically, what
the renormalon would be

00:39:54.170 --> 00:39:54.920
is the following.

00:39:54.920 --> 00:39:58.250
You would have an ambiguity
in the coefficient C0

00:39:58.250 --> 00:40:06.700
bar that's of the size lambda
QCD over whatever the scale

00:40:06.700 --> 00:40:07.240
Q is.

00:40:11.540 --> 00:40:17.950
And you would have the same
ambiguity in this theta 1 bar.

00:40:17.950 --> 00:40:20.470
So this theta 1 bar, which
is an MS-bar matrix element

00:40:20.470 --> 00:40:24.820
has an ambiguity, which
is of order lambda QCD.

00:40:24.820 --> 00:40:26.440
This guy has an ambiguity.

00:40:26.440 --> 00:40:28.570
And those ambiguities cancel.

00:40:28.570 --> 00:40:31.180
So you're dividing up the
physics again in MS-bar

00:40:31.180 --> 00:40:33.850
into short distance physics
and long distance physics.

00:40:33.850 --> 00:40:36.970
And the interesting
thing is that there's

00:40:36.970 --> 00:40:40.180
a piece of long distance
physics trapped in the C0

00:40:40.180 --> 00:40:42.340
that, if you really
wanted, should

00:40:42.340 --> 00:40:44.340
be physically in the theta
1 bar and vice versa.

00:40:47.450 --> 00:40:49.660
So really what's the
problem with MS-bar

00:40:49.660 --> 00:40:51.160
is that there's a
piece of something

00:40:51.160 --> 00:40:53.470
that you want in theta
1 bar, but ends up just

00:40:53.470 --> 00:40:55.710
being in the C0 bar.

00:40:55.710 --> 00:40:58.400
And that's what I mean by this
that there is something here,

00:40:58.400 --> 00:41:00.280
which is infrared sensitive.

00:41:00.280 --> 00:41:03.730
Correspondingly, there is kind
of an ultraviolet sensitivity

00:41:03.730 --> 00:41:04.660
in this theta 1 bar.

00:41:04.660 --> 00:41:07.013
And you'd like to
get that rearranged

00:41:07.013 --> 00:41:07.930
in an appropriate way.

00:41:07.930 --> 00:41:10.030
And that's like this
kind of rearrangement

00:41:10.030 --> 00:41:12.910
we were making by changing
schemes for masses.

00:41:12.910 --> 00:41:15.670
Except here it's going
to be changing schemes

00:41:15.670 --> 00:41:17.348
for Wilson coefficients.

00:41:20.220 --> 00:41:26.480
So this thing here is
what we would call a u

00:41:26.480 --> 00:41:28.253
equals 1 renormalon.

00:41:32.330 --> 00:41:34.860
So what happens
with u equals 1 is

00:41:34.860 --> 00:41:37.470
that you make a connection
between the leading order term

00:41:37.470 --> 00:41:40.370
and the power suppressed term.

00:41:40.370 --> 00:41:43.030
That's what happens
with the delta C0 bar.

00:41:47.100 --> 00:41:49.900
So in order to flesh out a
little bit better what I just

00:41:49.900 --> 00:41:52.240
said in words, let's
pretend that we

00:41:52.240 --> 00:41:53.530
understand what the theory is.

00:41:53.530 --> 00:41:55.280
And let's just pretend
it's some integral.

00:41:57.660 --> 00:42:00.160
And I'll just show you
what is going on here.

00:42:15.300 --> 00:42:20.503
Let's imagine that our
theory is an integral.

00:42:20.503 --> 00:42:21.920
Instead of a quantum
field theory,

00:42:21.920 --> 00:42:23.253
it's a one-dimensional integral.

00:42:27.510 --> 00:42:30.680
And it has two
scales, one which I'll

00:42:30.680 --> 00:42:33.800
call lambda QCD, which
is some low scale,

00:42:33.800 --> 00:42:39.170
and one which I'll call Q,
which is some high scale.

00:42:39.170 --> 00:42:42.500
And I'm using a notation where
the integral could diverge

00:42:42.500 --> 00:42:46.190
and I regulate it with a
dimensional regularization type

00:42:46.190 --> 00:42:46.800
parameter.

00:42:46.800 --> 00:42:48.383
So I'm doing a one
dimensional undergo

00:42:48.383 --> 00:42:50.415
but continuing it into
epsilon dimensions

00:42:50.415 --> 00:42:52.450
to regulate any divergences.

00:42:55.090 --> 00:42:59.540
So what MS-bar does with this
integral is it just says,

00:42:59.540 --> 00:43:02.920
well, I'm not going to change
the limits of the integral.

00:43:02.920 --> 00:43:05.110
I'm just going to
either expand out this f

00:43:05.110 --> 00:43:08.440
or expand out this denominator.

00:43:08.440 --> 00:43:10.000
I'll do two different
Taylor series,

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:12.250
and then I'll put them together.

00:43:12.250 --> 00:43:17.330
And that's basically how
I'm identifying the terms

00:43:17.330 --> 00:43:18.140
in my OPE.

00:43:22.330 --> 00:43:45.190
So MS-bar-- so I
sort of associate

00:43:45.190 --> 00:43:49.420
there being a high energy
piece where k is of order Q.

00:43:49.420 --> 00:43:53.253
And then there's some
low energy piece.

00:43:53.253 --> 00:43:54.295
I don't change the limit.

00:43:58.490 --> 00:44:02.230
So in the low energy piece,
I keep the full function f.

00:44:02.230 --> 00:44:05.830
And then I expand
out the other thing.

00:44:10.230 --> 00:44:13.360
And if I drop the
dots in this formula,

00:44:13.360 --> 00:44:16.720
I can identify these
integrals as toy models

00:44:16.720 --> 00:44:20.860
for the things that are
appearing in my OPE.

00:44:20.860 --> 00:44:22.270
So let me write that OPE again.

00:44:29.602 --> 00:44:33.100
So here these things
are 1, this example.

00:44:33.100 --> 00:44:35.860
This integral here, which
is over high energy scales

00:44:35.860 --> 00:44:38.140
k [INAUDIBLE] by Q is this guy.

00:44:40.980 --> 00:44:43.510
And this integral here, where
k is of order lambda QCD,

00:44:43.510 --> 00:44:45.190
effectively, there's
a 1 over Q, which

00:44:45.190 --> 00:44:49.630
is this 1 over Q. That's giving
me the operator, theta 1 bar.

00:44:52.700 --> 00:44:54.850
So Wilson coefficient
is the high energy piece

00:44:54.850 --> 00:44:57.250
of the original thing.

00:44:57.250 --> 00:44:59.080
Matrix element here is
the low energy piece

00:44:59.080 --> 00:45:04.420
which is suppressed by
1 over Q, but they both

00:45:04.420 --> 00:45:07.200
came from the same
physics in the beginning.

00:45:07.200 --> 00:45:08.950
And I just was expanding
it because that's

00:45:08.950 --> 00:45:10.117
how I wanted to organize it.

00:45:12.258 --> 00:45:14.800
Now, the thing about MS-bar is
that you integrate all the way

00:45:14.800 --> 00:45:15.700
down to 0 there.

00:45:15.700 --> 00:45:19.000
And you integrate all the
way up to infinity here.

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:21.160
And that's where the
renormalon problems come from.

00:45:31.330 --> 00:45:35.040
So this little procedure here
separates the long and short

00:45:35.040 --> 00:45:37.920
distance physics for the logs.

00:45:43.040 --> 00:45:46.100
It does that correctly.

00:45:46.100 --> 00:45:50.570
But for powers, we
effectively rely on the fact

00:45:50.570 --> 00:45:51.535
that it's at scale.

00:45:51.535 --> 00:45:52.670
This integral goes to 0.

00:45:58.940 --> 00:46:02.240
That's what's forced
upon us by the definition

00:46:02.240 --> 00:46:05.440
of MS-bar and dimensional
regularization.

00:46:08.582 --> 00:46:11.710
And what goes wrong is basically
that physically we're still

00:46:11.710 --> 00:46:14.770
integrating over regions of
those integrals which are not

00:46:14.770 --> 00:46:18.190
associated to the physics that
should be in those parameters.

00:47:01.140 --> 00:47:04.903
So, now, this is a toy
example, but the same thing

00:47:04.903 --> 00:47:06.570
is happening in the
quantum field theory

00:47:06.570 --> 00:47:09.070
when you think about what
you're doing when you write down

00:47:09.070 --> 00:47:11.470
Feynman diagram and you
construct a Wilson coefficient.

00:47:11.470 --> 00:47:14.053
It's effectively the same thing
in dimensional regularization.

00:47:14.053 --> 00:47:16.620
You're integrating over
all values of momentum.

00:47:16.620 --> 00:47:18.310
And this little
kind of toy analogy

00:47:18.310 --> 00:47:22.300
is actually apt for what's going
on in a true operator product

00:47:22.300 --> 00:47:24.730
expansion.

00:47:24.730 --> 00:47:30.650
What would happen if you did
a Wilsonian picture in our toy

00:47:30.650 --> 00:47:32.870
model?

00:47:32.870 --> 00:47:35.120
Well, then you would cut off
the integrals explicitly.

00:47:35.120 --> 00:47:40.660
You'd say, let's introduce
some scale lambda f.

00:47:40.660 --> 00:47:43.970
I could still think of it
expanding in the same way.

00:47:48.050 --> 00:47:50.882
I don't need the dimensional
regularization anymore.

00:47:50.882 --> 00:47:53.410
So I'll set that,
get rid of that.

00:47:56.873 --> 00:47:59.540
I think of breaking the integral
into two pieces, the low energy

00:47:59.540 --> 00:48:01.040
and high energy pieces.

00:48:01.040 --> 00:48:03.740
And in each of those pieces,
I expand the integral

00:48:03.740 --> 00:48:04.640
in different ways--

00:48:08.620 --> 00:48:13.160
so same type of expansion, I'm
just regulating it differently.

00:48:13.160 --> 00:48:15.510
Now, I'm guaranteed
that this is high energy

00:48:15.510 --> 00:48:18.120
and this is low energy.

00:48:18.120 --> 00:48:20.250
And you can write down
sort of what this is

00:48:20.250 --> 00:48:21.680
a proxy for as a Wilsonian OPE.

00:48:33.880 --> 00:48:37.560
Mu gets replaced by
the scale lambda f.

00:48:37.560 --> 00:48:39.360
Everything gets a
W for Wilsonian.

00:48:47.350 --> 00:48:50.680
Again, this is one
with our toy model.

00:48:50.680 --> 00:48:53.200
This guy is this guy now.

00:48:53.200 --> 00:48:56.270
This guy is this guy now.

00:48:56.270 --> 00:48:58.270
So it's a very similar
kind of association,

00:48:58.270 --> 00:48:59.770
but just the way
that we're treating

00:48:59.770 --> 00:49:01.740
the integral is different.

00:49:01.740 --> 00:49:04.090
In this way of doing things,
you don't have any problem

00:49:04.090 --> 00:49:06.020
with the renormalon.

00:49:06.020 --> 00:49:07.780
You just have an
explicit cutoff,

00:49:07.780 --> 00:49:10.900
which says there's no
low energy part of this,

00:49:10.900 --> 00:49:14.160
and there's no high
energy part of that.

00:49:14.160 --> 00:49:18.290
I'm not integrating
all the way down to 0

00:49:18.290 --> 00:49:20.517
in the first integral, so
I don't have any problems

00:49:20.517 --> 00:49:21.350
with the renormalon.

00:49:21.350 --> 00:49:24.020
The renormalon came from
infrared physics that

00:49:24.020 --> 00:49:26.990
was happening near k equals 0.

00:49:26.990 --> 00:49:30.750
And in this one, there's
no sort of problem

00:49:30.750 --> 00:49:34.510
which would come from infinity.

00:49:34.510 --> 00:49:39.000
So in some sense, this
is what we'd like to do.

00:49:46.110 --> 00:49:51.540
And the but here is that
it causes difficulties

00:49:51.540 --> 00:49:52.380
with symmetries.

00:49:59.800 --> 00:50:04.780
In particular, it generically
breaks gauge invariance

00:50:04.780 --> 00:50:07.007
and Lorentz invariance.

00:50:12.254 --> 00:50:15.330
These get broken.

00:50:15.330 --> 00:50:19.050
And the calculations
that you would like to do

00:50:19.050 --> 00:50:27.570
are just too difficult. I don't
know of anybody that's done--

00:50:27.570 --> 00:50:30.030
maybe somebody's done two
loops in the Wilsonian picture,

00:50:30.030 --> 00:50:32.580
but nobody's ever done three.

00:50:32.580 --> 00:50:35.820
So in some sense, you have
some nice things here.

00:50:35.820 --> 00:50:37.268
You have some nice things here.

00:50:37.268 --> 00:50:38.810
But they're not the
same nice things.

00:50:38.810 --> 00:50:41.735
And you'd like to have something
that does the best of both.

00:50:41.735 --> 00:50:43.110
And that's
effectively what we're

00:50:43.110 --> 00:50:45.395
doing when we construct
these R schemes.

00:50:45.395 --> 00:50:46.770
What we're doing
is we're saying,

00:50:46.770 --> 00:50:48.570
well, let's take MS-bar
as a starting point

00:50:48.570 --> 00:50:51.060
and try to get rid of
the problem that it has

00:50:51.060 --> 00:50:53.320
by perturbing towards
a Wilsonian picture.

00:51:00.160 --> 00:51:02.940
So what would an R
scheme OPEC look like?

00:51:07.200 --> 00:51:10.905
Start with MS-bar and
make a scheme change.

00:51:15.280 --> 00:51:28.660
And make a scheme change
here both to the operators

00:51:28.660 --> 00:51:32.093
and make the same scheme
change to the coefficient.

00:51:32.093 --> 00:51:33.760
So I'm just really
