01:01:52.880 --> 01:01:55.510
So I want to show you one
example of how this plays out

01:01:55.510 --> 01:01:57.020
in practice.

01:01:57.020 --> 01:02:00.200
And it's related to
our discussion of HQET.

01:02:00.200 --> 01:02:02.430
So one thing that
we said about HQET

01:02:02.430 --> 01:02:04.555
is that you could calculate
the following quantity.

01:02:16.195 --> 01:02:18.658
So HQET makes some
predictions about the B star

01:02:18.658 --> 01:02:19.950
and the B. They were connected.

01:02:19.950 --> 01:02:21.810
They were in a
symmetry multiplet.

01:02:21.810 --> 01:02:25.370
And when you took the
difference of the B star and B

01:02:25.370 --> 01:02:27.120
and you took this
combination, it actually

01:02:27.120 --> 01:02:28.245
is purely perturbative.

01:02:28.245 --> 01:02:30.120
Because there's a
non-perturbative parameter.

01:02:30.120 --> 01:02:32.440
But if you treat the
charm quark as heavy,

01:02:32.440 --> 01:02:34.380
it's the same for
charm and bottom.

01:02:34.380 --> 01:02:35.220
And it cancels out.

01:02:37.900 --> 01:02:42.130
So you can actually write down
an MS-bar operator product

01:02:42.130 --> 01:02:48.790
expansion, which is
technically defined in HQET.

01:02:48.790 --> 01:02:51.100
And what it looks like
is the first thing

01:02:51.100 --> 01:02:53.930
is just a ratio of
Wilson coefficients.

01:02:53.930 --> 01:02:55.957
So we talked about this.

01:02:55.957 --> 01:02:58.040
And we plugged in this
sort of leading log result.

01:02:58.040 --> 01:03:00.207
And we saw that it was
working actually pretty well.

01:03:03.950 --> 01:03:06.170
And if you were to kind
of look at higher order

01:03:06.170 --> 01:03:08.510
terms in that OPE, there would
be some power corrections

01:03:08.510 --> 01:03:09.010
to that.

01:03:11.682 --> 01:03:13.140
They've got some
traditional names.

01:03:13.140 --> 01:03:16.530
The names are not too important.

01:03:16.530 --> 01:03:20.517
But this is like the analog
of the 1 over Q term.

01:03:20.517 --> 01:03:21.600
This is the 1 over Q term.

01:03:21.600 --> 01:03:24.210
This is the leading order term,
which was purely perturbative.

01:03:24.210 --> 01:03:25.502
There's no matrix element here.

01:03:25.502 --> 01:03:26.640
It's just 1.

01:03:26.640 --> 01:03:28.680
This is a higher
dimension operator.

01:03:28.680 --> 01:03:34.260
This guy scales like lambda QCD
cubed over lambda QCD squared.

01:03:34.260 --> 01:03:35.930
This is just lambda QCD.

01:03:38.610 --> 01:03:41.307
So that's like the
lambda QCD over Q term.

01:03:41.307 --> 01:03:43.140
And this is the formula
you would write down

01:03:43.140 --> 01:03:45.182
if you wanted to make a
prediction for this thing

01:03:45.182 --> 01:03:49.380
at higher precision in MS-bar.

01:03:49.380 --> 01:03:51.930
So what happens if I think
about this perturbative result

01:03:51.930 --> 01:03:53.860
at higher orders?

01:03:53.860 --> 01:03:56.000
So people have actually
calculated that coefficient

01:03:56.000 --> 01:03:57.508
to three-loop order.

01:03:57.508 --> 01:03:58.800
And here's where it looks like.

01:04:02.190 --> 01:04:06.865
So at order alpha,
you get minus 0.113.

01:04:06.865 --> 01:04:11.930
At order alpha squared,
you get minus 0.078.

01:04:11.930 --> 01:04:19.174
And then you get another
minus 0.0755 at alpha cubed.

01:04:19.174 --> 01:04:22.683
It doesn't look so
pretty, all right?

01:04:22.683 --> 01:04:24.600
So each order that you
calculate is giving you

01:04:24.600 --> 01:04:29.040
a correction about the same
size as the previous order.

01:04:29.040 --> 01:04:31.230
Well, you might say, of
course, there's logs.

01:04:31.230 --> 01:04:33.600
So I should resum the logs.

01:04:33.600 --> 01:04:38.790
So let's resum the
logs, so leading log.

01:04:42.350 --> 01:04:45.360
And then since I have higher
order anomalous dimensions,

01:04:45.360 --> 01:04:49.440
let me put in next leading log.

01:04:49.440 --> 01:04:50.940
And actually, I
have one more order.

01:04:50.940 --> 01:05:00.300
So let me put that in, too,
[? 908 ?] next leading log.

01:05:00.300 --> 01:05:03.240
Uh-oh, all right?

01:05:03.240 --> 01:05:05.820
So this is the one that we
