01:06:00.220 --> 01:06:01.530
Switch to the MSR scheme.

01:06:07.720 --> 01:06:10.250
So we reuse our perturbative
information in MS-bar,

01:06:10.250 --> 01:06:13.240
but just organize in a
more intelligent fashion.

01:06:18.630 --> 01:06:34.493
So we define a
coefficient as above,

01:06:34.493 --> 01:06:35.910
saying that this
problem must have

01:06:35.910 --> 01:06:38.260
to do with that renormalon.

01:06:38.260 --> 01:06:47.790
And then if we write down
what the OPE looks like,

01:06:47.790 --> 01:06:51.680
we have, again, an OPE.

01:06:51.680 --> 01:06:54.270
And we've changed matrix
examined definitions as well

01:06:54.270 --> 01:06:57.060
as Wilson coefficients
definitions.

01:06:57.060 --> 01:06:59.070
So I'm putting everything
in this scale R0.

01:07:06.450 --> 01:07:09.090
So that's just rewriting
the OPE in this new scheme.

01:07:14.210 --> 01:07:17.670
When we look at this scheme and
we think about what's going on,

01:07:17.670 --> 01:07:20.710
we want to choose the
R0 to be of order lambda

01:07:20.710 --> 01:07:23.395
QCD or a bit bigger.

01:07:23.395 --> 01:07:24.770
And the reason we
want to do that

01:07:24.770 --> 01:07:26.030
is to preserve power counting.

01:07:30.480 --> 01:07:34.370
So power counting is important
when we're making expansions.

01:07:34.370 --> 01:07:37.530
In some sense, it's key.

01:07:37.530 --> 01:07:43.520
And if we thought that
the original MS-bar matrix

01:07:43.520 --> 01:07:47.040
element was dominated
by the scale lambda QCD,

01:07:47.040 --> 01:07:52.670
we better not screw that up when
we make a change of variable.

01:07:52.670 --> 01:07:59.145
And so the kind of change
of variable you're making

01:07:59.145 --> 01:08:01.020
is you're taking the
original matrix element.

01:08:01.020 --> 01:08:05.520
You're subtracting a series with
a proportionality constant R0.

01:08:05.520 --> 01:08:07.170
This guy was lambda QCD squared.

01:08:07.170 --> 01:08:11.950
And you want this to be not too
far different than lambda QCD,

01:08:11.950 --> 01:08:14.370
so that this whole thing
here is lambda QCD cubed just

01:08:14.370 --> 01:08:18.910
like this, so that
this thing is still

01:08:18.910 --> 01:08:21.064
of order lambda QCD cubed.

01:08:21.064 --> 01:08:22.439
So you don't want
to do something

01:08:22.439 --> 01:08:25.859
like choose the R0 to be Mb or
something because then you'd

01:08:25.859 --> 01:08:29.010
be making a huge change in the
value of this matrix element.

01:08:29.010 --> 01:08:31.790
You really want to take the
R0 cutoff to be of order,

01:08:31.790 --> 01:08:33.397
say, g of r or something.

01:08:37.069 --> 01:08:41.109
So you can use the RGE to sum
up logs from that scale R0

01:08:41.109 --> 01:08:42.090
up to the scale of MQ.

01:08:46.560 --> 01:08:52.149
So again, we can sum up logs and
have a logarithmically improved

01:08:52.149 --> 01:08:59.109
result. But actually the
most important thing here

01:08:59.109 --> 01:09:01.960
is getting rid of
the renormalon.

01:09:01.960 --> 01:09:04.270
I just wanted to
kind of show you

01:09:04.270 --> 01:09:09.920
what the result would look like
with both the RGE improvement,

01:09:09.920 --> 01:09:15.069
just sort of using the full
set of tools that we have.

01:09:15.069 --> 01:09:16.430
So here's the scales.

01:09:16.430 --> 01:09:20.000
You have three physical scales,
b quark mass, charm mass,

01:09:20.000 --> 01:09:21.319
lambda QCD.

01:09:21.319 --> 01:09:22.227
You have two cutoffs.

01:09:22.227 --> 01:09:23.810
You have our R0,
which I just told you

01:09:23.810 --> 01:09:26.390
you should pick to be
close to lambda QCD.

01:09:26.390 --> 01:09:29.800
And then you can think that
there's these other scales, Mb

01:09:29.800 --> 01:09:31.760
and M charm.

01:09:31.760 --> 01:09:34.170
If this is some low scale
and that's some high scale,

01:09:34.170 --> 01:09:35.359
I'd like to sum logs.

01:09:35.359 --> 01:09:39.350
And I can do that by
running up from R0 to R1,

01:09:39.350 --> 01:09:44.779
which in this case I'll just
pick between Mb and M charm.

01:09:44.779 --> 01:09:50.779
So if you did that,
you'd get some result

01:09:50.779 --> 01:09:58.230
that looks like
this, just putting

01:09:58.230 --> 01:10:00.400
in some notation for
the resummation here.

01:10:08.940 --> 01:10:10.565
And then this guy
is at the low scale.

01:10:20.477 --> 01:10:21.560
So now, everybody's happy.

01:10:21.560 --> 01:10:23.120
The Wilson coefficients
here can be expanded

01:10:23.120 --> 01:10:24.180
in perturbation theory.

01:10:24.180 --> 01:10:26.060
We don't think there's
any large logs.

01:10:26.060 --> 01:10:28.550
This U sums up any large
logs between the low scales

01:10:28.550 --> 01:10:29.960
and the high scales.

01:10:29.960 --> 01:10:33.560
And this guy's living at a
scale that he likes to live at.

01:10:33.560 --> 01:10:37.350
And there's no renormalon,
no u equals 1 renormalon.

01:10:37.350 --> 01:10:41.570
So what does it look like
if I write down this guy?

01:10:41.570 --> 01:10:44.570
So first of all, if I look
at this thing order by order,

01:10:44.570 --> 01:10:47.718
this is how the
