uncertainty from higher orders

01:11:40.930 --> 01:11:43.590
by varying scales.

01:11:43.590 --> 01:11:48.330
And you get a prediction
that looks like that.

01:11:48.330 --> 01:11:50.390
So when you want to
estimate uncertainties,

01:11:50.390 --> 01:11:52.940
what you typically do with
your cutoffs is you vary them.

01:11:52.940 --> 01:11:54.440
You say, well, it
has to be up here,

01:11:54.440 --> 01:11:56.000
but I don't have to
take it exactly there.

01:11:56.000 --> 01:11:58.170
I could take it up here
or take it a little lower,

01:11:58.170 --> 01:11:59.090
move this guy around.

01:11:59.090 --> 01:12:01.340
That gives you some idea of
higher order uncertainties

01:12:01.340 --> 01:12:03.380
because the dependence
on these scales

01:12:03.380 --> 01:12:06.190
cancels out order by order
in perturbation theory.

01:12:06.190 --> 01:12:08.990
And so varying it
is a way of getting

01:12:08.990 --> 01:12:10.680
an idea of higher
order uncertainties

01:12:10.680 --> 01:12:11.835
from perturbation theory.

01:12:11.835 --> 01:12:13.460
And that's what I've
done, for example,

01:12:13.460 --> 01:12:14.793
for this perturbative term here.

01:12:14.793 --> 01:12:19.490
This is varying R1 up and
down by a factor of 2.

01:12:19.490 --> 01:12:23.600
And just see kind of what
residual uncertainty you have.

01:12:23.600 --> 01:12:25.027
This one's more interesting.

01:12:25.027 --> 01:12:26.360
So that one's like mu variation.

01:12:26.360 --> 01:12:28.400
This one's more interesting.

01:12:28.400 --> 01:12:31.100
And that's because we have
this other cutoff, R0.

01:12:31.100 --> 01:12:35.210
But what R0 does is it
connects a leading order term

01:12:35.210 --> 01:12:37.690
to a sub-leading power term.

01:12:37.690 --> 01:12:40.460
The R0 dependence
cancels between something

01:12:40.460 --> 01:12:42.860
that's order 1 in the
power counting, something

01:12:42.860 --> 01:12:45.520
that's higher order
in the power counting.

01:12:45.520 --> 01:12:47.630
But when I vary R0,
it still cancels

01:12:47.630 --> 01:12:48.740
between these two pieces.

01:12:48.740 --> 01:12:52.370
Because remember, if you
look at the top of the board,

01:12:52.370 --> 01:12:56.350
I've included higher power
terms in my Wilson coefficient.

01:12:56.350 --> 01:12:59.000
And so varying the
R0, you can actually

01:12:59.000 --> 01:13:00.860
get an idea of how
big this thing is

01:13:00.860 --> 01:13:04.200
kind of in a naive
dimensional analysis type way.

01:13:04.200 --> 01:13:07.215
And not gives this number here.

01:13:07.215 --> 01:13:09.500
So R0 variation
actually allows you

01:13:09.500 --> 01:13:12.650
to test for the size of
the power corrections

01:13:12.650 --> 01:13:14.900
if you don't know them.

01:13:14.900 --> 01:13:17.720
And in this case, it turns out
that the power correction is

01:13:17.720 --> 01:13:19.500
kind of small in this scheme.

01:13:19.500 --> 01:13:21.410
But it didn't have
to be that small.

01:13:21.410 --> 01:13:24.810
It could have been 165, 265.

01:13:24.810 --> 01:13:27.770
It happens to be 0.065, OK?

01:13:27.770 --> 01:13:30.230
So everything looks
much nicer after we just

01:13:30.230 --> 01:13:31.607
get rid of the renormalon.

01:13:31.607 --> 01:13:33.440
Someone else did the
three-loop calculation.

01:13:33.440 --> 01:13:39.080
You made the prediction,
just true in this case.

01:13:41.880 --> 01:13:43.270
OK, so questions?

01:13:46.340 --> 01:13:50.930
So the moral of the story
is that, if you really

01:13:50.930 --> 01:13:54.225
want to use calculations
that are out there,

01:13:54.225 --> 01:13:55.725
you have to think
about the physics.

01:13:55.725 --> 01:13:57.805
You can't just calculate, sorry.

01:14:05.640 --> 01:14:08.490
So these renormalons, when
you have kind of order

01:14:08.490 --> 01:14:10.270
alpha squared or alpha
cubed information,

01:14:10.270 --> 01:14:12.187
then you have to worry
about things like this.

01:14:12.187 --> 01:14:14.820
And if you didn't, what looked
like was working beautifully

01:14:14.820 --> 01:14:17.490
at leading log order
might get spoiled.

01:14:17.490 --> 01:14:18.990
You're leading log
might be the best

01:14:18.990 --> 01:14:21.625
prediction unless you think
about this that you can make.

01:14:21.625 --> 01:14:23.250
Because your just
higher orders, you're

01:14:23.250 --> 01:14:25.960
getting sensitive to
this renormalon problem.

01:14:25.960 --> 01:14:30.480
And what that means is
generically this is changing

01:14:30.480 --> 01:14:32.225
and this is changing.

01:14:32.225 --> 01:14:33.600
The power correction
is changing.

01:14:33.600 --> 01:14:35.510
And so at each order
that this changes,

01:14:35.510 --> 01:14:37.800
I could compensate
by changing this.

01:14:37.800 --> 01:14:39.970
But it would have to be a
pretty big change, right?

01:14:39.970 --> 01:14:41.490
I changed this guy
by this amount.

01:14:41.490 --> 01:14:43.073
And then I have to
compensate by that.

01:14:43.073 --> 01:14:45.120
Whoops, now, it even
changes by a larger amount.

01:14:45.120 --> 01:14:48.780
Well, compensate by changing
this by order 1 amount.

01:14:48.780 --> 01:14:52.740
That's exactly this fact, that
both things have this problem.

01:14:52.740 --> 01:14:55.973
Order by order, I can
cancel out the problem,

01:14:55.973 --> 01:14:58.140
but then I can never really
assign a number to this.

01:14:58.140 --> 01:14:59.567
It's an order dependent number.

01:14:59.567 --> 01:15:01.650
Each order in perturbation
theory that I use here,

01:15:01.650 --> 01:15:02.940
this number changes.

01:15:02.940 --> 01:15:04.440
And that's not
really what you think

01:15:04.440 --> 01:15:06.212
of for a physical concept.

01:15:06.212 --> 01:15:07.920
This matrix element
should have a meaning

01:15:07.920 --> 01:15:10.320
that it shouldn't be
changing by order 1

01:15:10.320 --> 01:15:13.170
depending on the perturbative
order that you're working.

01:15:13.170 --> 01:15:14.880
In this way of
thinking, this thing

01:15:14.880 --> 01:15:17.780
is stable, much
more stable anyway.

01:15:17.780 --> 01:15:20.970
And you can assign
a number to it.

01:15:20.970 --> 01:15:24.210
That's kind of the moral.

